_⚠️ Potential issue_ | _🟡 Minor_ | _⚡ Quick win_

**Overlay state flickers after `AiPanelTrigger` opens the panel.**

When the panel is closed and the user clicks the Sparkles trigger, the sequence is:
1. `hideAiOverlay()` schedules a 220ms timeout that will eventually run `setLeftOverlayVisible(false)`.
2. `openAiPanel()` synchronously sets both `leftOpen=true` and `leftOverlayVisible=true`.
3. ~220ms later, the queued timeout fires and flips `leftOverlayVisible` back to `false`.

Since `AiSidebarTrigger` derives its icon (`Menu` vs `PanelLeftClose`), `title`, `aria-label`, and `aria-expanded` from `overlayVisible`, the adjacent button visibly flickers for ~220ms after every Sparkles click. The intermediate `overlayVisible=true` state is also inconsistent with the intent of opening the panel without the overlay menu.

Prefer synchronously reconciling the state — e.g. expose a `setOverlayVisible(false)` or open the panel without auto-showing the overlay — instead of relying on the deferred hide timeout to undo `openAiPanel()`.



<details>
<summary>🛠️ One option: invert the order and add an immediate hide</summary>

In `PanelProviders`, either change `openLeft` not to force `overlayVisible=true`, or add a synchronous hide action used by `AiPanelTrigger`:

```diff
 const hideLeftOverlay = useCallback(() => {
   if (leftOverlayHideTimeoutRef.current) {
     clearTimeout(leftOverlayHideTimeoutRef.current);
   }
   leftOverlayHideTimeoutRef.current = setTimeout(() => {
     setLeftOverlayVisible(false);
     leftOverlayHideTimeoutRef.current = null;
   }, 220);
 }, []);
+const hideLeftOverlayImmediate = useCallback(() => {
+  if (leftOverlayHideTimeoutRef.current) {
+    clearTimeout(leftOverlayHideTimeoutRef.current);
+    leftOverlayHideTimeoutRef.current = null;
+  }
+  setLeftOverlayVisible(false);
+}, []);
```

Then have `AiPanelTrigger` call `openAiPanel()` first, followed by the immediate hide, so React batches both state updates into a single render with `open=true, overlayVisible=false`.
</details>

